  <h2>THE POTENTIAL OF POSTAL WORKERS IN SENIOR CARE
  </h2>

  <p>
    Across the globe, successful examples of senior check-in services delivered by postal workers, including the “Mimamori” program from Japan Post and the “Veiller sur mes parents” program from the French La Poste, already exist.
  </p>
  <p>Additionally, since 2016, the Canadian Union of Postal Workers has been advocating for Canada Post to leverage its unique positioning and network of over (12540 + 28,400) letter carriers to establish a check-in service for seniors.</p>
  <p>Furthermore, the National Institute on Ageing (NIA), a research centre based at Toronto Metropolitan University, also advocates that Canada Post is in a unique position to deliver such a service. Citing a poll conducted by Leger conducted in 2015, they state that letter carriers are amongst the most trusted professions in Canada, with 87% of Canadians saying they trusted their mail carriers.</p>
  <p>Although the proposal was modelled from overseas solutions, there was definitely opportunity within Canada’s seniors as well, with Statistics Canada reporting that 1 in 4 Canadians will be over the age of 65 by 2030 (in comparison to 15.3% in 2013), and the NIA and Canadian Medical Association reporting that 96% of Canadians want to age at home for as long as possible.</p>
  
  <h2>Ideation</h2>
  <h3>PROPERLY SCOPING WHAT A POSTAL WORKER CAN AND CANNOT DO
  </h3>
  <p>It is important to note that initial proposals of Carriers that Care were met with a lot of hesitation from user testers. Having conducted user interviews with seven individuals with ages ranging from 20s to 50s, centering our questions around allowed us to sort concerns into four categories:</p>
  
  
  <h2>Phase 1: Setting up visits</h2>

  <p>
    Audience would familiarize themselves with our service through the landing
    page of the service. Here, we outline a description of the service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ensuring that loved ones have consented to the service, Canada Post will ask
    for contact information of both the loved one and family. The final step of
    the sign-up process will involve the senior recipient of the service, with
    Canada Post reaching out through a phone call to ensure that seniors will be
    aware of the service. Carriers that Care will not begin until this step is
    completed.
  </p>
  <h2>Phase 2: Postal Worker App</h2>
  <div style="padding:56.25% 0 0 0;position:relative;">
    <iframe
      src="https://vimeo.com/902242958/4c1c822fc3?share=copy"
      style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;"
      frameborder="0"
      allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture"
      allowfullscreen></iframe>
  </div>
  <p>
    Postal workers can use this app to quickly send reports and access resources
    they may need during the visits.
  </p>
  <p>
    Steps involved in reporting will include reporting on their well-being,
    reporting on topics of interest, and et cetra.
  </p>
  <p>
    Following the visit, Postal worker will fill out and upload a report on
    observations they made during the visit. Reports will be optimized for
    Postal workers to be able to fill out while on-the-go.
  </p>
  <p>
    Should any unexpected events occur during the visits, we plan equip postal
    workers with an ‘emergency resources’ page on the app. Addtionally, we
    through Canada Post’s exisiting training portal, we expect carriers to be
    able to handle certain events to some degree.
  </p>
  <h2>Phase 3: Post-Visit Updates</h2>
  <div style="padding:56.25% 0 0 0;position:relative;">
    <iframe
      src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/902436807?h=752ba33798"
